# @orbit/tools

Orbit's model-agnostic tool framework. Implements the infrastructure future
tools (shell, filesystem, git, browser, ...) will plug into — this package
contains no AI, agent, planner, or provider logic, and no tools beyond
lightweight demonstrations.

## Install (editable, local development)

```bash
pip install -e ".[dev]"
```

## Concepts

- **`Tool`** — abstract base every tool implements: a `metadata` property,
  `validate(arguments)`, and `async execute(arguments, context)`. Call
  `tool.run(arguments, context)` to get a `ToolResult` back — it never
  raises, converting validation/execution failures into
  `ToolResult(success=False, error=...)`.
- **`ToolMetadata`** — a tool's name, description, JSON-Schema-like
  `parameters`, and version.
- **`ToolContext`** — reusable per-invocation context (task id, request id,
  permissions, config, metadata, cooperative cancellation). Structure only;
  this package never populates or interprets it beyond `is_cancelled()`.
- **`ToolResult`** — standardized outcome: `success`, `output`, `error`,
  `execution_time`, `metadata`.
- **`ToolRegistry`** — registers, unregisters, discovers (`list()`), and
  invokes (`invoke(name, arguments, context)`) tools by name. Callers never
  instantiate a tool directly.

## Built-in demonstration tools

`EchoTool`, `TimeTool`, `SystemInfoTool` — trivial tools proving the
architecture works end-to-end. Not meant to be useful on their own.

## Usage

```python
from orbit_tools import EchoTool, ToolContext, ToolRegistry

registry = ToolRegistry()
registry.register(EchoTool())

result = await registry.invoke("echo", {"message": "hi"}, ToolContext())
result.success         # True
result.output          # {"echo": "hi"}
result.execution_time  # seconds, float
```

## Adding a real tool later

- Subclass `Tool`, implement `metadata` and `execute`.
- Register it with the process-wide `ToolRegistry` in
  `apps/api/src/orbit_api/core/tools.py` — route handlers should not
  import or instantiate tool classes directly.
- This package should never import `orbit_runtime`, a provider, or a
  planner; those subsystems depend on tools, not the other way around.
